00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.260
what it'd be like to
come to the Googleplex,

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:14.750
meet up with a Googler,
and have coffee with them.

00:00:14.750 --> 00:00:17.340
And just chat about what
they do, how they do it,

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:18.420
and why they do it.

00:00:18.420 --> 00:00:20.360
And today we're going
to do exactly that.

00:00:22.175 --> 00:00:24.300
LAURENCE MORONEY: Welcome
to Coffee with a Googler.

00:00:24.300 --> 00:00:26.383
I'm Laurence Moroney and
I'm here in New York City

00:00:26.383 --> 00:00:27.940
to meet with Roman Nurik.

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:31.140
And Roman Nurik is one of
our material design gurus

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:31.890
here at Google.

00:00:31.890 --> 00:00:34.887
So material design, tell
me what's it all about.

00:00:34.887 --> 00:00:35.970
ROMAN NURIK: Oh, Laurence.

00:00:35.970 --> 00:00:39.412
What is material design?

00:00:39.412 --> 00:00:40.620
It's kind of hard to explain.

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:44.240
There's actually a video with a
bunch of the original designers

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:45.920
that created material
design and they

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:47.770
get asked the same
question and they

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:49.480
don't know how to answer it.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:51.530
It is a complex kind of thing.

00:00:51.530 --> 00:00:53.890
There's a lot of
things going on.

00:00:53.890 --> 00:00:56.700
I guess is the most basic
level, it's a design language.

00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:59.040
It's a design system.

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:02.120
It covers visual interaction
and motion design.

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:05.630
I feel like most design
systems, design languages,

00:01:05.630 --> 00:01:07.500
are treated as just
visual languages.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.090
Like here are the colors
you should use, and so on.

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:12.600
But material is
much more than that.

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:15.690
It really kind of
covers the model,

00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:18.520
the underlying physical
model, of the UI.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:21.230
So it basically
tries to establish

00:01:21.230 --> 00:01:25.850
this physical environment within
which your apps should live.

00:01:25.850 --> 00:01:28.800
On a phone, on a
tablet, on a computer,

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:31.330
basically any sort of screen.

00:01:31.330 --> 00:01:32.860
And then it
basically establishes

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:34.318
this physical
environment and a set

00:01:34.318 --> 00:01:37.470
of basic rules and principles.

00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:41.260
And I like to think of it along
these kind of four basic axes,

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:43.340
or four basic principles.

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:45.350
And that's tangible surfaces.

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:46.980
Work on the material metaphor.

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.130
We can talk about what
material is at some point.

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:52.010
Also bold graphic design.

00:01:52.010 --> 00:01:56.220
This idea that we should take
some of the best design ideas

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:00.030
from the print world and see
how they can help us make really

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:04.380
great apps on digital devices.

00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:05.870
And the third is
meaningful motion.

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:10.190
Basically how all these
things, how these surfaces,

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:14.830
and the ink on that surface,
the graphic design stuff,

00:02:14.830 --> 00:02:18.860
how that all moves in a
consistent way to help

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:20.187
communicate what's going on.

00:02:20.187 --> 00:02:22.770
And the fourth thing, which is
to me one of the most important

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:24.860
things, is adaptive design.

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:28.120
Which is how can we take
all these first three things

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:30.790
and make sure that
they work consistently

00:02:30.790 --> 00:02:33.495
and coherently across different
devices, phones and tablets,

00:02:33.495 --> 00:02:34.590
and everything else.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:36.506
LAURENCE MORONEY: Now
you have a video, right,

00:02:36.506 --> 00:02:39.180
of some really good examples
of material design being used.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.620
So should we roll that?

