00:05:44.056 --> 00:05:46.180
LAURENCE MORONEY: So back
to material design again.

00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:48.500
Why material?

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:51.370
ROMAN NURIK: So material goes
back to that first principle.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:54.210
So this idea of
tangible surfaces.

00:05:54.210 --> 00:06:00.150
This idea that everything on
your screen and your device

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:02.190
exists on a surface.

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:05.470
We like to think of
them as pieces of paper.

00:06:05.470 --> 00:06:09.310
So basically you can think of
basically a sheet of material

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:12.480
or the word material
representing

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:14.180
one of those pieces of paper.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:15.680
And the reason we
don't just call it

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:18.930
paper is because it actually
is a lot more than just paper.

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.340
In the real world paper,
once you rip it up

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:23.370
you can't really just
put it back together.

00:06:23.370 --> 00:06:27.030
And paper can't go from
being a circle to a square

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:28.550
to a rectangle.

00:06:28.550 --> 00:06:31.900
And so we like to think of our
digital pieces of material,

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:37.470
or sheets of material, as
kind of a smarter paper.

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.390
Still a constrained paper,
you can just do anything.

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:43.400
It can't just do all
sorts of crazy things,

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:46.440
but it is a physical
thing that exists inside

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.240
of this kind of
environment, this kind

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:50.550
of like faux environment.

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:54.200
But it is something that has
a lot of thought put into it.

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:57.080
And so the word
material to me really

00:06:57.080 --> 00:07:01.410
means, the sheets of paper
that everything in this world

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:02.540
exists on.

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:05.690
But for me is the main
thing to think about,

00:07:05.690 --> 00:07:08.620
the reason that motion is so
important in material design

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:12.130
is that motion should
always have meaning.

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:15.910
Try not to just do it
like a flip of a button,

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:18.017
or like a double rotation,
or something just

00:07:18.017 --> 00:07:19.100
to kind of draw attention.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:22.305
Every time something moves
it attracts our attention

00:07:22.305 --> 00:07:23.930
and so it needs to
be really thoughtful

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:26.300
and really carefully
planned out.

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:31.310
And so in material, we use
motion just enough motion

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:34.800
to convey the change
in some object's state

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:37.670
or try to get a little
bit of attention.

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:40.090
But just enough motion not
too little, not too much.

